# Domain Aggregates

## State

- All fields are `private` with underscore prefix (`_status`, `_assignedUnits`).
- Expose read-only state via `getSnapshot()`, never via public fields.

## Public commands

- Return `Result<void, DomainError>` – never throw for expected business rule violations.
- Follow the pattern: guard → compute candidate state → validate → mutate.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
public addPalletUnit(unit, ldmProvider): Result<void, DomainError> {
  const guardResult = this.ensurePlanNotFinalized();
  if (!guardResult.success) return guardResult;

  const candidateUnits = [...this._assignedUnits, unit];
  const newLdm = ldmProvider(candidateUnits, this._trailer);
  const integrityResult = this.ensureLoadIntegrity(candidateUnits, this._trailer, newLdm);
  if (!integrityResult.success) return integrityResult;

  this._assignedUnits = candidateUnits;   // mutate only after all checks pass
  this._currentLdm = newLdm;
  return ok(undefined);
}
```

## `ensure___` methods – consistency guards

- Name every guard method `ensure<WhatIsEnforced>` (e.g. `ensurePlanNotFinalized`, `ensureWeightCapacityNotExceeded`).
- **One rule per method** – each `ensure___` checks exactly one invariant and returns early.
- Return `Result<void, SpecificError>` – use the most specific error type, not the union.
- Never mutate state inside an `ensure___` method.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD – single responsibility
private ensureWeightCapacityNotExceeded(
  units: PalletUnit[],
  trailer: PalletLoadableTrailerSpec
): Result<void, WeightCapacityExceededError> {
  const totalKg = units.reduce((sum, u) => sum + u.weight.valueInKg, 0);
  if (totalKg > trailer.maxWeightCapacity.valueInKg) {
    return fail(new WeightCapacityExceededError(totalKg, trailer.maxWeightCapacity.valueInKg));
  }
  return ok(undefined);
}

// ❌ BAD – mixing two rules in one method
private ensureCapacities(...): Result<void, DomainError> {
  if (weight > max) return fail(...);
  if (ldm > maxLdm) return fail(...);  // extract to ensureLdmCapacityNotExceeded
}
```

- Orchestrate multiple guards in a dedicated `ensure<GroupName>` method (e.g. `ensureLoadIntegrity`):

```typescript
private ensureLoadIntegrity(units, trailer, ldm): Result<void, DomainError> {
  if (units.length === 0) return ok(undefined);

  const weightResult = this.ensureWeightCapacityNotExceeded(units, trailer);
  if (!weightResult.success) return weightResult;

  const ldmResult = this.ensureLdmCapacityNotExceeded(ldm, trailer);
  if (!ldmResult.success) return ldmResult;

  // ...more guards
  return ok(undefined);
}
```

## Errors

- Plain classes with `readonly kind = 'XxxError' as const` (discriminated union, no `instanceof`).
- Collect all errors in `*.errors.ts` and export the union type as `<Aggregate>DomainError`.
- Constructor arguments carry the context needed to build `message` (actual vs. allowed values).

## Reconstruction invariants

- Call `ensureLoadIntegrity` (or equivalent) in the constructor when rebuilding from persistence.
- **Throw** (don't return `Result`) on constructor integrity failure – corrupt DB state is unexpected.
